CLINICAL HISTORY: Reason: standing ap Lateral and sunrise
No acute fracture is identified. The alignment is normal.
There are bony defects with sclerosis in the distal femur and
proximal tibia, more likely due to prior anterior cruciate ligament ..
There are degenerative changes with moderate narrowing of the
patellofemoral space and mild narrowing at the medial and lateral
femoral tibial joint spaces. There is spurring at the patella and
minimal marginal osteophyte formation at the medial and lateral
There is a well-corticated bony opacity below the patella which may
be due to old trauma or a loose body.
